        <li>Docs:<br>        """Add a dense index using Faiss for fast retrieval.
<br>
        The index is created using the vectors of the specified column.
<br>
        You can specify `device` if you want to run it on GPU (`device` must be the GPU index, see more below).
<br>
        You can find more information about Faiss here:
<br>
        - For `string factory`: https://github.com/facebookresearch/faiss/wiki/The-index-factory
<br>

<br>
        Args:
<br>
            column (`str`): The column of the vectors to add to the index.
<br>
            index_name (Optional `str`): The index_name/identifier of the index. This is the index_name that is used to call `.get_nearest` or `.search`.
<br>
                By default it corresponds to `column`.
<br>
            device (Optional `Union[int, List[int]]`): If positive integer, this is the index of the GPU to use. If negative integer, use all GPUs.
<br>
                If a list of positive integers is passed in, run only on those GPUs. By default it uses the CPU.
<br>
            string_factory (Optional `str`): This is passed to the index factory of Faiss to create the index. Default index class is IndexFlatIP.
<br>
            metric_type (Optional `int`): Type of metric. Ex: `faiss.METRIC_INNER_PRODUCT` or `faiss.METRIC_L2`.
<br>
            custom_index (Optional `faiss.Index`): Custom Faiss index that you already have instantiated and configured for your needs.
<br>
            batch_size (Optional `int`): Size of the batch to use while adding vectors to the FaissIndex. Default value is 1000.
<br>
                <Added version="2.4.0"/>
<br>
            train_size (Optional `int`): If the index needs a training step, specifies how many vectors will be used to train the index.
<br>
            faiss_verbose (`bool`, defaults to False): Enable the verbosity of the Faiss index.
<br>
        """
<br>

        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>matched_rel_path:  str,<br>pattern:  str,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """
<br>
    When a path matches a pattern, we additionnally check if it's inside a special directory
<br>
    we ignore by default (if it starts with a double underscore).
<br>

<br>
    Users can still explicitly request a filepath inside such a directory if "__pycache__" is
<br>
    mentioned explicitly in the requested pattern.
<br>

<br>
    Some examples:
<br>

<br>
    base directory:
<br>

<br>
        ./
<br>
        └── __pycache__
<br>
            └── b.txt
<br>

<br>
    >>> _is_inside_unrequested_special_dir("__pycache__/b.txt", "**")
<br>
    True
<br>
    >>> _is_inside_unrequested_special_dir("__pycache__/b.txt", "*/b.txt")
<br>
    True
<br>
    >>> _is_inside_unrequested_special_dir("__pycache__/b.txt", "__pycache__/*")
<br>
    False
<br>
    >>> _is_inside_unrequested_special_dir("__pycache__/b.txt", "__*/*")
<br>
    False
<br>
    """
<br>
</li>
        </ul>
    </details>
    <details>
        <summary>
        function | <a name='repos/datasets/src/datasets/data_files.py:_is_unrequested_hidden_file_or_is_inside_unrequested_hidden_dir' href='.//repos/datasets/src/datasets/data_files.py#L199'>_is_unrequested_hidden_file_or_is_inside_unrequested_hidden_dir</a>
        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>matched_rel_path:  str,<br>pattern:  str,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """
<br>
    When a path matches a pattern, we additionnally check if it's a hidden file or if it's inside
<br>
    a hidden directory we ignore by default, i.e. if the file name or a parent directory name starts with a dot.
<br>

<br>
    Users can still explicitly request a filepath that is hidden or is inside a hidden directory
<br>
    if the hidden part is mentioned explicitly in the requested pattern.
<br>

<br>
    Some examples:
<br>

<br>
    base directory:
<br>

<br>
        ./
<br>
        └── .hidden_file.txt
<br>

<br>
    >>> _is_unrequested_hidden_file_or_is_inside_unrequested_hidden_dir(".hidden_file.txt", "**")
<br>
    True
<br>
    >>> _is_unrequested_hidden_file_or_is_inside_unrequested_hidden_dir(".hidden_file.txt", ".*")
<br>
    False
<br>

<br>
    base directory:
<br>

<br>
        ./
<br>
        └── .hidden_dir
<br>
            └── a.txt
<br>

<br>
    >>> _is_unrequested_hidden_file_or_is_inside_unrequested_hidden_dir(".hidden_dir/a.txt", "**")
<br>
    True
<br>
    >>> _is_unrequested_hidden_file_or_is_inside_unrequested_hidden_dir(".hidden_dir/a.txt", ".*/*")
<br>
    False
<br>
    >>> _is_unrequested_hidden_file_or_is_inside_unrequested_hidden_dir(".hidden_dir/a.txt", ".hidden_dir/*")
<br>
    False
<br>

<br>
    base directory:
<br>

<br>
        ./
<br>
        └── .hidden_dir
<br>
            └── .hidden_file.txt
<br>

<br>
    >>> _is_unrequested_hidden_file_or_is_inside_unrequested_hidden_dir(".hidden_dir/.hidden_file.txt", "**")
<br>
    True
<br>
    >>> _is_unrequested_hidden_file_or_is_inside_unrequested_hidden_dir(".hidden_dir/.hidden_file.txt", ".*/*")
<br>
    True
<br>
    >>> _is_unrequested_hidden_file_or_is_inside_unrequested_hidden_dir(".hidden_dir/.hidden_file.txt", ".*/.*")
<br>
    False
<br>
    >>> _is_unrequested_hidden_file_or_is_inside_unrequested_hidden_dir(".hidden_dir/.hidden_file.txt", ".hidden_dir/*")
<br>
    True
<br>
    >>> _is_unrequested_hidden_file_or_is_inside_unrequested_hidden_dir(".hidden_dir/.hidden_file.txt", ".hidden_dir/.*")
<br>
    False
<br>
    """
<br>
</li>
        </ul>

        function | <a name='repos/datasets/src/datasets/data_files.py:resolve_pattern' href='.//repos/datasets/src/datasets/data_files.py#L320'>resolve_pattern</a>
        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>pattern:  str,<br>base_path:  str,<br>allowed_extensions:  Optional[List[str]]  =  None,<br>download_config:  Optional[DownloadConfig]  =  None,<br>,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """
<br>
    Resolve the paths and URLs of the data files from the pattern passed by the user.
<br>

<br>
    You can use patterns to resolve multiple local files. Here are a few examples:
<br>
    - *.csv to match all the CSV files at the first level
<br>
    - **.csv to match all the CSV files at any level
<br>
    - data/* to match all the files inside "data"
<br>
    - data/** to match all the files inside "data" and its subdirectories
<br>

<br>
    The patterns are resolved using the fsspec glob. In fsspec>=2023.12.0 this is equivalent to
<br>
    Python's glob.glob, Path.glob, Path.match and fnmatch where ** is unsupported with a prefix/suffix
<br>
    other than a forward slash /.
<br>

<br>
    More generally:
<br>
    - '*' matches any character except a forward-slash (to match just the file or directory name)
<br>
    - '**' matches any character including a forward-slash /
<br>

<br>
    Hidden files and directories (i.e. whose names start with a dot) are ignored, unless they are explicitly requested.
<br>
    The same applies to special directories that start with a double underscore like "__pycache__".
<br>
    You can still include one if the pattern explicilty mentions it:
<br>
    - to include a hidden file: "*/.hidden.txt" or "*/.*"
<br>
    - to include a hidden directory: ".hidden/*" or ".*/*"
<br>
    - to include a special directory: "__special__/*" or "__*/*"
<br>

<br>
    Example::
<br>

<br>
        >>> from datasets.data_files import resolve_pattern
<br>
        >>> base_path = "."
<br>
        >>> resolve_pattern("docs/**/*.py", base_path)
<br>
        [/Users/mariosasko/Desktop/projects/datasets/docs/source/_config.py']
<br>

<br>
    Args:
<br>
        pattern (str): Unix pattern or paths or URLs of the data files to resolve.
<br>
            The paths can be absolute or relative to base_path.
<br>
            Remote filesystems using fsspec are supported, e.g. with the hf:// protocol.
<br>
        base_path (str): Base path to use when resolving relative paths.
<br>
        allowed_extensions (Optional[list], optional): White-list of file extensions to use. Defaults to None (all extensions).
<br>
            For example: allowed_extensions=[".csv", ".json", ".txt", ".parquet"]
<br>
    Returns:
<br>
        List[str]: List of paths or URLs to the local or remote files that match the patterns.
<br>
    """
<br>

<a name='repos/datasets/src/datasets/utils/sharding.py' href='.//repos/datasets/src/datasets/utils/sharding.py'>repos/datasets/src/datasets/utils/sharding.py</a>

<ul>
    <details>
        <summary>
        function | <a name='repos/datasets/src/datasets/utils/sharding.py:_distribute_shards' href='.//repos/datasets/src/datasets/utils/sharding.py#L25'>_distribute_shards</a>
        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>num_shards:  int,<br>max_num_jobs:  int,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """
<br>
    Get the range of shard indices per job.
<br>
    If num_shards<max_num_jobs, then num_shards jobs are given a range of one shard.
<br>
    The shards indices order is preserved: e.g. all the first shards are given the first job.
<br>
    Moreover all the jobs are given approximately the same number of shards.
<br>

<br>
    Example:
<br>

    <details>
        <summary>
        function | <a name='repos/datasets/src/datasets/combine.py:concatenate_datasets' href='.//repos/datasets/src/datasets/combine.py#L158'>concatenate_datasets</a>
        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>dsets:  List[DatasetType],<br>info:  Optional[DatasetInfo]  =  None,<br>split:  Optional[NamedSplit]  =  None,<br>axis:  int  =  0,<br>,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """
<br>
    Converts a list of [`Dataset`] with the same schema into a single [`Dataset`].
<br>

<br>
    Args:
<br>
        dsets (`List[datasets.Dataset]`):
<br>
            List of Datasets to concatenate.
<br>
        info (`DatasetInfo`, *optional*):
<br>
            Dataset information, like description, citation, etc.
<br>
        split (`NamedSplit`, *optional*):
<br>
            Name of the dataset split.
<br>
        axis (`{0, 1}`, defaults to `0`):
<br>
            Axis to concatenate over, where `0` means over rows (vertically) and `1` means over columns
<br>
            (horizontally).
<br>

<br>
            <Added version="1.6.0"/>
<br>

<br>
    Example:
<br>

<br>
    ```py
<br>
    >>> ds3 = concatenate_datasets([ds1, ds2])
<br>
    ```
<br>
    """
<br>
</li>
        </ul>
    </details>
    <details>
        <summary>
        function | <a name='repos/datasets/src/datasets/combine.py:interleave_datasets' href='.//repos/datasets/src/datasets/combine.py#L18'>interleave_datasets</a>
        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>datasets:  List[DatasetType],<br>probabilities:  Optional[List[float]]  =  None,<br>seed:  Optional[int]  =  None,<br>info:  Optional[DatasetInfo]  =  None,<br>split:  Optional[NamedSplit]  =  None,<br>stopping_strategy:  Literal["first_exhausted",<br>"all_exhausted"]  =  "first_exhausted",<br>,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """
<br>
    Interleave several datasets (sources) into a single dataset.
<br>
    The new dataset is constructed by alternating between the sources to get the examples.
<br>

<br>
    You can use this function on a list of [`Dataset`] objects, or on a list of [`IterableDataset`] objects.
<br>

<br>
        - If `probabilities` is `None` (default) the new dataset is constructed by cycling between each source to get the examples.
<br>
        - If `probabilities` is not `None`, the new dataset is constructed by getting examples from a random source at a time according to the provided probabilities.
<br>

<br>
    The resulting dataset ends when one of the source datasets runs out of examples except when `oversampling` is `True`,
<br>
    in which case, the resulting dataset ends when all datasets have ran out of examples at least one time.
<br>

<br>
    Note for iterable datasets:
<br>

<br>
    In a distributed setup or in PyTorch DataLoader workers, the stopping strategy is applied per process.
<br>
    Therefore the "first_exhausted" strategy on an sharded iterable dataset can generate less samples in total (up to 1 missing sample per subdataset per worker).
<br>

<br>
    Args:
<br>
        datasets (`List[Dataset]` or `List[IterableDataset]`):
<br>
            List of datasets to interleave.
<br>
        probabilities (`List[float]`, *optional*, defaults to `None`):
<br>
            If specified, the new dataset is constructed by sampling
<br>
            examples from one source at a time according to these probabilities.
<br>
        seed (`int`, *optional*, defaults to `None`):
<br>
            The random seed used to choose a source for each example.
<br>
        info ([`DatasetInfo`], *optional*):
<br>
            Dataset information, like description, citation, etc.
<br>
            <Added version="2.4.0"/>
<br>
        split ([`NamedSplit`], *optional*):
<br>
            Name of the dataset split.
<br>
            <Added version="2.4.0"/>
<br>
        stopping_strategy (`str`, defaults to `first_exhausted`):
<br>
            Two strategies are proposed right now, `first_exhausted` and `all_exhausted`.
<br>
            By default, `first_exhausted` is an undersampling strategy, i.e the dataset construction is stopped as soon as one dataset has ran out of samples.
<br>
            If the strategy is `all_exhausted`,  we use an oversampling strategy, i.e the dataset construction is stopped as soon as every samples of every dataset has been added at least once.
<br>
            Note that if the strategy is `all_exhausted`, the interleaved dataset size can get enormous:
<br>
            - with no probabilities, the resulting dataset will have `max_length_datasets*nb_dataset` samples.
<br>
            - with given probabilities, the resulting dataset will have more samples if some datasets have really low probability of visiting.
<br>
    Returns:
<br>
        [`Dataset`] or [`IterableDataset`]: Return type depends on the input `datasets`
<br>
        parameter. `Dataset` if the input is a list of `Dataset`, `IterableDataset` if the input is a list of
<br>
        `IterableDataset`.
<br>

<br>
    Example:
<br>

<br>
        For regular datasets (map-style):
<br>

<br>
        ```python
<br>
        >>> from datasets import Dataset, interleave_datasets
<br>
        >>> d1 = Dataset.from_dict({"a": [0, 1, 2]})
<br>
        >>> d2 = Dataset.from_dict({"a": [10, 11, 12]})
<br>
        >>> d3 = Dataset.from_dict({"a": [20, 21, 22]})
<br>
        >>> dataset = interleave_datasets([d1, d2, d3], probabilities=[0.7, 0.2, 0.1], seed=42, stopping_strategy="all_exhausted")

        >>> dataset = interleave_datasets([d1, d2, d3], probabilities=[0.7, 0.2, 0.1], seed=42)
<br>
        >>> dataset["a"]
<br>
        [10, 0, 11, 1, 2]
<br>
        >>> dataset = interleave_datasets([d1, d2, d3])
<br>
        >>> dataset["a"]
<br>
        [0, 10, 20, 1, 11, 21, 2, 12, 22]
<br>
        >>> dataset = interleave_datasets([d1, d2, d3], stopping_strategy="all_exhausted")
<br>
        >>> dataset["a"]
<br>
        [0, 10, 20, 1, 11, 21, 2, 12, 22]
<br>

        >>> d2 = Dataset.from_dict({"a": [10, 11, 12, 13]})
<br>
        >>> d3 = Dataset.from_dict({"a": [20, 21, 22, 23, 24]})
<br>
        >>> dataset = interleave_datasets([d1, d2, d3])
<br>
        >>> dataset["a"]
<br>
        [0, 10, 20, 1, 11, 21, 2, 12, 22]
<br>
        >>> dataset = interleave_datasets([d1, d2, d3], stopping_strategy="all_exhausted")
<br>
        >>> dataset["a"]
<br>
        [0, 10, 20, 1, 11, 21, 2, 12, 22, 0, 13, 23, 1, 10, 24]
<br>
        >>> dataset = interleave_datasets([d1, d2, d3], probabilities=[0.7, 0.2, 0.1], seed=42)
<br>
        >>> dataset["a"]
<br>

<br>
        >>> dataset = interleave_datasets([d1, d2, d3], probabilities=[0.7, 0.2, 0.1], seed=42, stopping_strategy="all_exhausted")
<br>
        >>> dataset["a"]
<br>
        [10, 0, 11, 1, 2, 20, 12, 13, ..., 0, 1, 2, 0, 24]
<br>
        For datasets in streaming mode (iterable):

        >>> d1 = load_dataset("oscar", "unshuffled_deduplicated_en", split="train", streaming=True)
        ```

        <ul>

        <ul>path:  str,<br>revision:  Optional[Union[str,<br>Version]]  =  None,<br>download_config:  Optional[DownloadConfig]  =  None,<br>download_mode:  Optional[Union[DownloadMode,<br>str]]  =  None,<br>dynamic_modules_path:  Optional[str]  =  None,<br>data_dir:  Optional[str]  =  None,<br>data_files:  Optional[Union[Dict,<br>List,<br>str,<br>DataFilesDict]]  =  None,<br>cache_dir:  Optional[str]  =  None,<br>trust_remote_code:  Optional[bool]  =  None,<br>_require_default_config_name = True,<br>_require_custom_configs = False,<br>**download_kwargs,<br>,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """
<br>
    Download/extract/cache a dataset module.
<br>

<br>
    Dataset codes are cached inside the dynamic modules cache to allow easy import (avoid ugly sys.path tweaks).
<br>

<br>
    Args:
<br>

<br>
        path (str): Path or name of the dataset.
<br>
            Depending on ``path``, the dataset builder that is used comes from a generic dataset script (JSON, CSV, Parquet, text etc.) or from the dataset script (a python file) inside the dataset directory.
<br>

<br>
            For local datasets:
<br>

<br>
            - if ``path`` is a local directory (containing data files only)
<br>
              -> load a generic dataset builder (csv, json, text etc.) based on the content of the directory
<br>
              e.g. ``'./path/to/directory/with/my/csv/data'``.
<br>
            - if ``path`` is a local dataset script or a directory containing a local dataset script (if the script has the same name as the directory):
<br>
              -> load the dataset builder from the dataset script
<br>
              e.g. ``'./dataset/squad'`` or ``'./dataset/squad/squad.py'``.
<br>

<br>
            For datasets on the Hugging Face Hub (list all available datasets with ``huggingface_hub.list_datasets()``)
<br>

<br>
            - if ``path`` is a dataset repository on the HF hub (containing data files only)
<br>
              -> load a generic dataset builder (csv, text etc.) based on the content of the repository
<br>
              e.g. ``'username/dataset_name'``, a dataset repository on the HF hub containing your data files.
<br>
            - if ``path`` is a dataset repository on the HF hub with a dataset script (if the script has the same name as the directory)
<br>
              -> load the dataset builder from the dataset script in the dataset repository
<br>
              e.g. ``glue``, ``squad``, ``'username/dataset_name'``, a dataset repository on the HF hub containing a dataset script `'dataset_name.py'`.
<br>

<br>
        revision (:class:`~utils.Version` or :obj:`str`, optional): Version of the dataset script to load.
<br>
            As datasets have their own git repository on the Datasets Hub, the default version "main" corresponds to their "main" branch.
<br>
            You can specify a different version than the default "main" by using a commit SHA or a git tag of the dataset repository.
<br>
        download_config (:class:`DownloadConfig`, optional): Specific download configuration parameters.
<br>
        download_mode (:class:`DownloadMode` or :obj:`str`, default ``REUSE_DATASET_IF_EXISTS``): Download/generate mode.
<br>
        dynamic_modules_path (Optional str, defaults to HF_MODULES_CACHE / "datasets_modules", i.e. ~/.cache/huggingface/modules/datasets_modules):
<br>
            Optional path to the directory in which the dynamic modules are saved. It must have been initialized with :obj:`init_dynamic_modules`.
<br>
            By default, the datasets and metrics are stored inside the `datasets_modules` module.
<br>
        data_dir (:obj:`str`, optional): Directory with the data files. Used only if `data_files` is not specified,
<br>
            in which case it's equal to pass `os.path.join(data_dir, "**")` as `data_files`.
<br>
        data_files (:obj:`Union[Dict, List, str]`, optional): Defining the data_files of the dataset configuration.
<br>
        cache_dir (`str`, *optional*):
<br>
            Directory to read/write data. Defaults to `"~/.cache/huggingface/datasets"`.
<br>

<br>
            <Added version="2.16.0"/>
<br>
        trust_remote_code (`bool`, defaults to `True`):
<br>
            Whether or not to allow for datasets defined on the Hub using a dataset script. This option
<br>
            should only be set to `True` for repositories you trust and in which you have read the code, as it will
<br>
            execute code present on the Hub on your local machine.
<br>

<br>
            <Tip warning={true}>
<br>

<br>
            `trust_remote_code` will default to False in the next major release.
<br>

<br>
            </Tip>

<br>
            <Added version="2.16.0"/>
<br>
        **download_kwargs (additional keyword arguments): optional attributes for DownloadConfig() which will override
<br>
            the attributes in download_config if supplied.
<br>

<br>
    Returns:
<br>
        DatasetModule
<br>
    """

        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>path:  str,<br>name:  Optional[str]  =  None,<br>data_dir:  Optional[str]  =  None,<br>data_files:  Optional[Union[str,<br>Sequence[str],<br>Mapping[str,<br>Union[str,<br>Sequence[str]]]]]  =  None,<br>split:  Optional[Union[str,<br>Split]]  =  None,<br>cache_dir:  Optional[str]  =  None,<br>features:  Optional[Features]  =  None,<br>download_config:  Optional[DownloadConfig]  =  None,<br>download_mode:  Optional[Union[DownloadMode,<br>str]]  =  None,<br>verification_mode:  Optional[Union[VerificationMode,<br>str]]  =  None,<br>ignore_verifications = "deprecated",<br>keep_in_memory:  Optional[bool]  =  None,<br>save_infos:  bool  =  False,<br>revision:  Optional[Union[str,<br>Version]]  =  None,<br>token:  Optional[Union[bool,<br>str]]  =  None,<br>use_auth_token = "deprecated",<br>task = "deprecated",<br>streaming:  bool  =  False,<br>num_proc:  Optional[int]  =  None,<br>storage_options:  Optional[Dict]  =  None,<br>trust_remote_code:  bool  =  None,<br>**config_kwargs,<br>,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """Load a dataset from the Hugging Face Hub, or a local dataset.
<br>

<br>
    You can find the list of datasets on the [Hub](https://huggingface.co/datasets) or with [`huggingface_hub.list_datasets`].
<br>

<br>
    A dataset is a directory that contains:
<br>

<br>
    - some data files in generic formats (JSON, CSV, Parquet, text, etc.).
<br>
    - and optionally a dataset script, if it requires some code to read the data files. This is used to load any kind of formats or structures.
<br>

<br>
    Note that dataset scripts can also download and read data files from anywhere - in case your data files already exist online.
<br>

<br>
    This function does the following under the hood:
<br>

<br>
        1. Download and import in the library the dataset script from `path` if it's not already cached inside the library.
<br>

<br>
            If the dataset has no dataset script, then a generic dataset script is imported instead (JSON, CSV, Parquet, text, etc.)
<br>

<br>
            Dataset scripts are small python scripts that define dataset builders. They define the citation, info and format of the dataset,
<br>
            contain the path or URL to the original data files and the code to load examples from the original data files.
<br>

<br>
            You can find the complete list of datasets in the Datasets [Hub](https://huggingface.co/datasets).
<br>

<br>
        2. Run the dataset script which will:
<br>

<br>
            * Download the dataset file from the original URL (see the script) if it's not already available locally or cached.
<br>
            * Process and cache the dataset in typed Arrow tables for caching.
<br>

<br>
                Arrow table are arbitrarily long, typed tables which can store nested objects and be mapped to numpy/pandas/python generic types.
<br>
                They can be directly accessed from disk, loaded in RAM or even streamed over the web.
<br>

<br>
        3. Return a dataset built from the requested splits in `split` (default: all).
<br>

<br>
    It also allows to load a dataset from a local directory or a dataset repository on the Hugging Face Hub without dataset script.
<br>
    In this case, it automatically loads all the data files from the directory or the dataset repository.
<br>

<br>
    Args:
<br>

<br>
        path (`str`):
<br>
            Path or name of the dataset.
<br>
            Depending on `path`, the dataset builder that is used comes from a generic dataset script (JSON, CSV, Parquet, text etc.) or from the dataset script (a python file) inside the dataset directory.
<br>

<br>
            For local datasets:
<br>

<br>
            - if `path` is a local directory (containing data files only)
<br>
              -> load a generic dataset builder (csv, json, text etc.) based on the content of the directory
<br>
              e.g. `'./path/to/directory/with/my/csv/data'`.
<br>
            - if `path` is a local dataset script or a directory containing a local dataset script (if the script has the same name as the directory)
<br>
              -> load the dataset builder from the dataset script
<br>
              e.g. `'./dataset/squad'` or `'./dataset/squad/squad.py'`.
<br>

<br>
            For datasets on the Hugging Face Hub (list all available datasets with [`huggingface_hub.list_datasets`])
<br>

<br>
            - if `path` is a dataset repository on the HF hub (containing data files only)
<br>
              -> load a generic dataset builder (csv, text etc.) based on the content of the repository
<br>
              e.g. `'username/dataset_name'`, a dataset repository on the HF hub containing your data files.
<br>
            - if `path` is a dataset repository on the HF hub with a dataset script (if the script has the same name as the directory)
<br>
              -> load the dataset builder from the dataset script in the dataset repository
<br>
              e.g. `glue`, `squad`, `'username/dataset_name'`, a dataset repository on the HF hub containing a dataset script `'dataset_name.py'`.
<br>

<br>
        name (`str`, *optional*):
<br>
            Defining the name of the dataset configuration.
<br>
        data_dir (`str`, *optional*):
<br>
            Defining the `data_dir` of the dataset configuration. If specified for the generic builders (csv, text etc.) or the Hub datasets and `data_files` is `None`,
<br>
            the behavior is equal to passing `os.path.join(data_dir, **)` as `data_files` to reference all the files in a directory.
<br>
        data_files (`str` or `Sequence` or `Mapping`, *optional*):
<br>
            Path(s) to source data file(s).
<br>
        split (`Split` or `str`):
<br>
            Which split of the data to load.
<br>
            If `None`, will return a `dict` with all splits (typically `datasets.Split.TRAIN` and `datasets.Split.TEST`).
<br>
            If given, will return a single Dataset.
<br>
            Splits can be combined and specified like in tensorflow-datasets.
<br>
        cache_dir (`str`, *optional*):
<br>
            Directory to read/write data. Defaults to `"~/.cache/huggingface/datasets"`.
<br>
        features (`Features`, *optional*):
<br>
            Set the features type to use for this dataset.
<br>
        download_config ([`DownloadConfig`], *optional*):
<br>
            Specific download configuration parameters.
<br>
        download_mode ([`DownloadMode`] or `str`, defaults to `REUSE_DATASET_IF_EXISTS`):
<br>
            Download/generate mode.
<br>
        verification_mode ([`VerificationMode`] or `str`, defaults to `BASIC_CHECKS`):
<br>
            Verification mode determining the checks to run on the downloaded/processed dataset information (checksums/size/splits/...).
<br>

<br>
            <Added version="2.9.1"/>
<br>
        ignore_verifications (`bool`, defaults to `False`):
<br>
            Ignore the verifications of the downloaded/processed dataset information (checksums/size/splits/...).
<br>

<br>
            <Deprecated version="2.9.1">
<br>

<br>
            `ignore_verifications` was deprecated in version 2.9.1 and will be removed in 3.0.0.
<br>
            Please use `verification_mode` instead.
<br>

<br>
            </Deprecated>
<br>
        keep_in_memory (`bool`, defaults to `None`):
<br>
            Whether to copy the dataset in-memory. If `None`, the dataset
<br>
            will not be copied in-memory unless explicitly enabled by setting `datasets.config.IN_MEMORY_MAX_SIZE` to
<br>
            nonzero. See more details in the [improve performance](../cache#improve-performance) section.
<br>
        save_infos (`bool`, defaults to `False`):
<br>
            Save the dataset information (checksums/size/splits/...).
<br>
        revision ([`Version`] or `str`, *optional*):
<br>
            Version of the dataset script to load.
<br>
            As datasets have their own git repository on the Datasets Hub, the default version "main" corresponds to their "main" branch.
<br>
            You can specify a different version than the default "main" by using a commit SHA or a git tag of the dataset repository.
<br>
        token (`str` or `bool`, *optional*):
<br>
            Optional string or boolean to use as Bearer token for remote files on the Datasets Hub.
<br>
            If `True`, or not specified, will get token from `"~/.huggingface"`.
<br>
        use_auth_token (`str` or `bool`, *optional*):
<br>
            Optional string or boolean to use as Bearer token for remote files on the Datasets Hub.
<br>
            If `True`, or not specified, will get token from `"~/.huggingface"`.
<br>

<br>
            <Deprecated version="2.14.0">
<br>

<br>
            `use_auth_token` was deprecated in favor of `token` in version 2.14.0 and will be removed in 3.0.0.
<br>

<br>
            </Deprecated>
<br>
        task (`str`):
<br>

<br>

<br>

<br>
    - some data files in generic formats (JSON, CSV, Parquet, text, etc.)
<br>
    - and optionally a dataset script, if it requires some code to read the data files. This is used to load any kind of formats or structures.
<br>

<br>

<br>

<br>

<br>

<br>
            - if `path` is a local directory (containing data files only)
<br>

<br>
              e.g. `'./path/to/directory/with/my/csv/data'`.
<br>

<br>
              -> load the dataset builder from the dataset script
<br>
              e.g. `'./dataset/squad'` or `'./dataset/squad/squad.py'`.
<br>

<br>

<br>

<br>

<br>

        <li>Docs:<br>    """
<br>
    Given something that might be a URL (or might be a local path),
<br>
    determine which. If it's a URL, download the file and cache it, and
<br>
    return the path to the cached file. If it's already a local path,
<br>
    make sure the file exists and then return the path.
<br>

<br>
    Return:
<br>
        Local path (string)
<br>

<br>
    Raises:
<br>
        FileNotFoundError: in case of non-recoverable file
<br>

        <li>Args:</li>

        <li>Docs:<br>    """
<br>
    This function extends os.path.basename to support the "::" hop separator. It supports both paths and urls.
<br>

<br>
    A shorthand, particularly useful where you have multiple hops, is to “chain” the URLs with the special separator "::".
<br>
    This is used to access files inside a zip file over http for example.
<br>

<br>
    Let's say you have a zip file at https://host.com/archive.zip, and you want to access the file inside the zip file at /folder1/file.txt.
<br>
    Then you can just chain the url this way:
<br>

<br>
        zip://folder1/file.txt::https://host.com/archive.zip
<br>

<br>
    The xbasename function allows you to apply the basename on the first path of the chain.
<br>

<br>
    Example::
<br>

<br>
        >>> xbasename("zip://folder1/file.txt::https://host.com/archive.zip")
<br>
        file.txt
<br>
    """
<br>
</li>

        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>a,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """
<br>
    This function extends os.path.split to support the "::" hop separator. It supports both paths and urls.
<br>

<br>
    A shorthand, particularly useful where you have multiple hops, is to “chain” the URLs with the special separator "::".
<br>
    This is used to access files inside a zip file over http for example.
<br>

<br>
    Let's say you have a zip file at https://host.com/archive.zip, and you want to access the file inside the zip file at /folder1/file.txt.
<br>
    Then you can just chain the url this way:
<br>

<br>
        zip://folder1/file.txt::https://host.com/archive.zip
<br>

<br>
    The xsplit function allows you to apply the xsplit on the first path of the chain.
<br>

<br>
    Example::
<br>

<br>
        >>> xsplit("zip://folder1/file.txt::https://host.com/archive.zip")
<br>
        ('zip://folder1::https://host.com/archive.zip', 'file.txt')
<br>
    """
<br>
</li>
        </ul>

<summary>
<a name='repos/llama_index/benchmarks/embeddings/bench_embeddings.py' href='.//repos/llama_index/benchmarks/embeddings/bench_embeddings.py'>repos/llama_index/benchmarks/embeddings/bench_embeddings.py</a>
</summary>
<ul>
    <details>
        <summary>
        function | <a name='repos/llama_index/benchmarks/embeddings/bench_embeddings.py:generate_strings' href='.//repos/llama_index/benchmarks/embeddings/bench_embeddings.py#L14'>generate_strings</a>
        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>num_strings:  int  =  100,<br>string_length:  int  =  10,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """
<br>
    Generate random strings sliced from the paul graham essay of the following form:
<br>

<br>
    offset 0: [0:string_length], [string_length:2*string_length], ...
<br>
    offset 1: [1:1+string_length], [1+string_length:1+2*string_length],...
<br>
    ...
<br>
    """  # noqa: D415
<br>
    content = (
<br>
        SimpleDirectoryReader("../../examples/paul_graham_essay/data")
<br>
        .load_data()[0]
<br>
        .get_content()
<br>
    )
<br>
    content_length = len(content)
<br>

<br>
    strings_per_loop = content_length / string_length
<br>
    num_loops_upper_bound = int(num_strings / strings_per_loop) + 1
<br>
    strings = []
<br>

<br>
    for offset in range(num_loops_upper_bound + 1):
<br>
        ptr = offset % string_length
<br>
        while ptr + string_length < content_length:
<br>
            strings.append(content[ptr : ptr + string_length])
<br>
            ptr += string_length
<br>
            if len(strings) == num_strings:
<br>
                break
<br>

<br>
    return strings
<br>

<br>

<br>
def create_open_ai_embedding(batch_size: int) -> Tuple[BaseEmbedding, str, int]:
<br>
    return (
<br>
        OpenAIEmbedding(embed_batch_size=batch_size),
<br>
        "OpenAIEmbedding",
<br>
        4096,
<br>
    )
<br>

<br>

<br>
def create_local_embedding(
<br>
    model_name: str, batch_size: int
<br>
) -> Tuple[BaseEmbedding, str, int]:
<br>
    model = resolve_embed_model(f"local:{model_name}")
<br>
    return (
<br>
        model,
<br>
        "hf/" + model_name,
<br>
        model._langchain_embedding.client.max_seq_length,  # type: ignore
<br>
    )
<br>

<br>

) -> None:
<br>
    """Benchmark embeddings."""

<br>
    It works recursively.
<br>

<br>
    If `optimize_list_casting` is True, to avoid iterating over possibly long lists, it first checks (recursively) if the first element that is not None or empty (if it is a sequence) has to be casted.
<br>
    If the first element needs to be casted, then all the elements of the list will be casted, otherwise they'll stay the same.
<br>
    This trick allows to cast objects that contain tokenizers outputs without iterating over every single token for example.
<br>

    Args:

        obj: the object (nested struct) to cast.
<br>
        only_1d_for_numpy (bool): whether to keep the full multi-dim tensors as multi-dim numpy arrays, or convert them to
<br>
            nested lists of 1-dimensional numpy arrays. This can be useful to keep only 1-d arrays to instantiate Arrow arrays.
<br>
            Indeed Arrow only support converting 1-dimensional array values.
<br>
        optimize_list_casting (bool): whether to optimize list casting by checking the first non-null element to see if it needs to be casted
<br>
            and if it doesn't, not checking the rest of the list elements.
<br>

<br>
    Returns:
<br>
        casted_obj: the casted object
<br>
        has_changed (bool): True if the object has been changed, False if it is identical
<br>
    """

        </summary>
        <ul>

        <ul>obj:  Any,<br>only_1d_for_numpy = False,<br>optimize_list_casting = True,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """
<br>
    Cast numpy/pytorch/tensorflow/pandas objects to python lists.
<br>
    It works recursively.
<br>

<br>
    If `optimize_list_casting` is True, To avoid iterating over possibly long lists, it first checks (recursively) if the first element that is not None or empty (if it is a sequence) has to be casted.
<br>
    If the first element needs to be casted, then all the elements of the list will be casted, otherwise they'll stay the same.
<br>
    This trick allows to cast objects that contain tokenizers outputs without iterating over every single token for example.
<br>

<br>
    Args:
<br>
        obj: the object (nested struct) to cast
<br>
        only_1d_for_numpy (bool, default ``False``): whether to keep the full multi-dim tensors as multi-dim numpy arrays, or convert them to
<br>
            nested lists of 1-dimensional numpy arrays. This can be useful to keep only 1-d arrays to instantiate Arrow arrays.
<br>
            Indeed Arrow only support converting 1-dimensional array values.
<br>
        optimize_list_casting (bool, default ``True``): whether to optimize list casting by checking the first non-null element to see if it needs to be casted
<br>
            and if it doesn't, not checking the rest of the list elements.
<br>

<br>
    Returns:
<br>
        casted_obj: the casted object
<br>
    """
<br>

        <ul>

        <ul>self,<br>max_depth = 16,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>        """Flatten the features. Every dictionary column is removed and is replaced by
<br>
        all the subfields it contains. The new fields are named by concatenating the
<br>
        name of the original column and the subfield name like this: `<original>.<subfield>`.
<br>

<br>
        If a column contains nested dictionaries, then all the lower-level subfields names are
<br>
        also concatenated to form new columns: `<original>.<subfield>.<subsubfield>`, etc.
<br>

<br>
        Returns:
<br>
            [`Features`]:
<br>
                The flattened features.
<br>

<br>
        Example:
<br>

<br>
        ```py
<br>
        >>> from datasets import load_dataset
<br>
        >>> ds = load_dataset("squad", split="train")
<br>
        >>> ds.features.flatten()
<br>
        {'answers.answer_start': Sequence(feature=Value(dtype='int32', id=None), length=-1, id=None),
<br>
         'answers.text': Sequence(feature=Value(dtype='string', id=None), length=-1, id=None),
<br>
         'context': Value(dtype='string', id=None),
<br>
         'id': Value(dtype='string', id=None),
<br>
         'question': Value(dtype='string', id=None),
<br>
         'title': Value(dtype='string', id=None)}
<br>
        ```
<br>
        """

        </ul>

    <details>

        method | <a name='repos/datasets/src/datasets/features/features.py:Features:from_dict' href='.//repos/datasets/src/datasets/features/features.py#L1725'>Features:from_dict</a>
        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>cls,<br>dic,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>        """
<br>
        Construct [`Features`] from dict.
<br>

<br>
        Regenerate the nested feature object from a deserialized dict.
<br>
        We use the `_type` key to infer the dataclass name of the feature `FieldType`.
<br>

<br>
        It allows for a convenient constructor syntax
<br>
        to define features from deserialized JSON dictionaries. This function is used in particular when deserializing
<br>
        a [`DatasetInfo`] that was dumped to a JSON object. This acts as an analogue to
<br>
        [`Features.from_arrow_schema`] and handles the recursive field-by-field instantiation, but doesn't require
<br>
        any mapping to/from pyarrow, except for the fact that it takes advantage of the mapping of pyarrow primitive
<br>
        dtypes that [`Value`] automatically performs.
<br>

<br>
        Args:
<br>
            dic (`dict[str, Any]`):
<br>
                Python dictionary.
<br>

<br>
        Returns:
<br>
            `Features`
<br>

<br>
        Example::
<br>
            >>> Features.from_dict({'_type': {'dtype': 'string', 'id': None, '_type': 'Value'}})
<br>
            {'_type': Value(dtype='string', id=None)}
<br>
        """
<br>
</li>
        </ul>
    </details>
    <details>
        <summary>
        method | <a name='repos/datasets/src/datasets/features/features.py:Features:reorder_fields_as' href='.//repos/datasets/src/datasets/features/features.py#L2049'>Features:reorder_fields_as</a>
        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>self,<br>other:  "Features",<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>        """
<br>
        Reorder Features fields to match the field order of other [`Features`].
<br>

<br>
        The order of the fields is important since it matters for the underlying arrow data.
<br>
        Re-ordering the fields allows to make the underlying arrow data type match.
<br>

<br>
        Args:
<br>
            other ([`Features`]):
<br>
                The other [`Features`] to align with.
<br>

<br>
        Returns:
<br>
            [`Features`]
<br>

<br>
        Example::
<br>

<br>
            >>> from datasets import Features, Sequence, Value
<br>
            >>> # let's say we have to features with a different order of nested fields (for a and b for example)
<br>
            >>> f1 = Features({"root": Sequence({"a": Value("string"), "b": Value("string")})})
<br>
            >>> f2 = Features({"root": {"b": Sequence(Value("string")), "a": Sequence(Value("string"))}})
<br>
            >>> assert f1.type != f2.type
<br>
            >>> # re-ordering keeps the base structure (here Sequence is defined at the root level), but make the fields order match
<br>
            >>> f1.reorder_fields_as(f2)
<br>
            {'root': Sequence(feature={'b': Value(dtype='string', id=None), 'a': Value(dtype='string', id=None)}, length=-1, id=None)}
<br>
            >>> assert f1.reorder_fields_as(f2).type == f2.type
<br>
        """
<br>
</li>
        </ul>
    </details>

        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """
<br>
    When applying transforms on a dataset, the data are stored in cache files.
<br>
    The caching mechanism allows to reload an existing cache file if it's already been computed.
<br>

<br>
    Reloading a dataset is possible since the cache files are named using the dataset fingerprint, which is updated
<br>
    after each transform.
<br>

<br>
    If disabled, the library will no longer reload cached datasets files when applying transforms to the datasets.
<br>
    More precisely, if the caching is disabled:
<br>
    - cache files are always recreated
<br>
    - cache files are written to a temporary directory that is deleted when session closes
<br>
    - cache files are named using a random hash instead of the dataset fingerprint
<br>
    - use [`~datasets.Dataset.save_to_disk`] to save a transformed dataset or it will be deleted when session closes
<br>
    - caching doesn't affect [`~datasets.load_dataset`]. If you want to regenerate a dataset from scratch you should use
<br>
    the `download_mode` parameter in [`~datasets.load_dataset`].
<br>
    """
<br>
</li>
        </ul>

        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>inplace:  bool,<br>use_kwargs:  Optional[List[str]]  =  None,<br>ignore_kwargs:  Optional[List[str]]  =  None,<br>fingerprint_names:  Optional[List[str]]  =  None,<br>randomized_function:  bool  =  False,<br>version:  Optional[str]  =  None,<br>,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """
<br>
    Wrapper for dataset transforms to update the dataset fingerprint using ``update_fingerprint``
<br>
    Args:
<br>
        inplace (:obj:`bool`):  If inplace is True, the fingerprint of the dataset is updated inplace.
<br>
            Otherwise, a parameter "new_fingerprint" is passed to the wrapped method that should take care of
<br>
            setting the fingerprint of the returned Dataset.
<br>
        use_kwargs (:obj:`List[str]`, optional): optional white list of argument names to take into account
<br>
            to update the fingerprint to the wrapped method that should take care of
<br>
            setting the fingerprint of the returned Dataset. By default all the arguments are used.
<br>
        ignore_kwargs (:obj:`List[str]`, optional): optional black list of argument names to take into account
<br>
            to update the fingerprint. Note that ignore_kwargs prevails on use_kwargs.
<br>
        fingerprint_names (:obj:`List[str]`, optional, defaults to ["new_fingerprint"]):
<br>
            If the dataset transforms is not inplace and returns a DatasetDict, then it can require
<br>
            several fingerprints (one per dataset in the DatasetDict). By specifying fingerprint_names,
<br>
            one fingerprint named after each element of fingerprint_names is going to be passed.
<br>
        randomized_function (:obj:`bool`, defaults to False): If the dataset transform is random and has
<br>
            optional parameters "seed" and "generator", then you can set randomized_function to True.
<br>
            This way, even if users set "seed" and "generator" to None, then the fingerprint is
<br>
            going to be randomly generated depending on numpy's current state. In this case, the
<br>
            generator is set to np.random.default_rng(np.random.get_state()[1][0]).
<br>
        version (:obj:`str`, optional): version of the transform. The version is taken into account when
<br>
            computing the fingerprint. If a datase transform changes (or at least if the output data
<br>
            that are cached changes), then one should increase the version. If the version stays the
<br>
            same, then old cached data could be reused that are not compatible with the new transform.
<br>
            It should be in the format "MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH".
<br>
    """
<br>

        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """
<br>
    When applying transforms on a dataset, the data are stored in cache files.
<br>
    The caching mechanism allows to reload an existing cache file if it's already been computed.
<br>

<br>
    Reloading a dataset is possible since the cache files are named using the dataset fingerprint, which is updated
<br>
    after each transform.
<br>

<br>
    If disabled, the library will no longer reload cached datasets files when applying transforms to the datasets.
<br>
    More precisely, if the caching is disabled:
<br>
    - cache files are always recreated
<br>
    - cache files are written to a temporary directory that is deleted when session closes
<br>
    - cache files are named using a random hash instead of the dataset fingerprint
<br>
    - use [`~datasets.Dataset.save_to_disk`]] to save a transformed dataset or it will be deleted when session closes
<br>
    - caching doesn't affect [`~datasets.load_dataset`]. If you want to regenerate a dataset from scratch you should use
<br>
    the `download_mode` parameter in [`~datasets.load_dataset`].
<br>
    """
<br>

        <li>Docs:<br>    """Decorator to flag a feature as experimental.
<br>

<br>
    An experimental feature trigger a warning when used as it might be subject to breaking changes in the future.
<br>

<br>
    Args:
<br>
        fn (`Callable`):
<br>
            The function to flag as experimental.
<br>

<br>
    Returns:
<br>
        `Callable`: The decorated function.
<br>

<br>
    Example:
<br>

<br>
    ```python
<br>
    >>> from datasets.utils import experimental
<br>

<br>
    >>> @experimental
<br>
    ... def my_function():
<br>
    ...     print("Hello world!")
<br>

<br>
    >>> my_function()
<br>
    UserWarning: 'my_function' is experimental and might be subject to breaking changes in the future.
<br>
    Hello world!
<br>
    ```
<br>
    """
<br>
</li>
        </ul>

        <li>Docs:<br>    """
<br>
    Format a Table depending on the key that was used and a Formatter object.
<br>

<br>
    Args:
<br>
        table (``datasets.table.Table``): The input Table to format
<br>
        key (``Union[int, slice, range, str, Iterable]``): Depending on the key that was used, the formatter formats
<br>
            the table as either a row, a column or a batch.
<br>
        formatter (``datasets.formatting.formatting.Formatter``): Any subclass of a Formatter such as
<br>
            PythonFormatter, NumpyFormatter, etc.
<br>
        format_columns (:obj:`List[str]`, optional): if not None, it defines the columns that will be formatted using the
<br>
            given formatter. Other columns are discarded (unless ``output_all_columns`` is True)
<br>
        output_all_columns (:obj:`bool`, defaults to False). If True, the formatted output is completed using the columns
<br>
            that are not in the ``format_columns`` list. For these columns, the PythonFormatter is used.
<br>

<br>

<br>
    Returns:
<br>
        A row, column or batch formatted object defined by the Formatter:
<br>
        - the PythonFormatter returns a dictionary for a row or a batch, and a list for a column.
<br>
        - the NumpyFormatter returns a dictionary for a row or a batch, and a np.array for a column.
<br>
        - the PandasFormatter returns a pd.DataFrame for a row or a batch, and a pd.Series for a column.
<br>
        - the TorchFormatter returns a dictionary for a row or a batch, and a torch.Tensor for a column.
<br>
        - the TFFormatter returns a dictionary for a row or a batch, and a tf.Tensor for a column.
<br>
    """
<br>

        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>table:  Table,<br>key:  Union[int,<br>slice,<br>range,<br>str,<br>Iterable],<br>indices:  Optional[Table]  =  None,<br>,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """
<br>
    Query a Table to extract the subtable that correspond to the given key.
<br>

<br>
    Args:
<br>
        table (``datasets.table.Table``): The input Table to query from
<br>
        key (``Union[int, slice, range, str, Iterable]``): The key can be of different types:
<br>
            - an integer i: the subtable containing only the i-th row
<br>
            - a slice [i:j:k]: the subtable containing the rows that correspond to this slice
<br>
            - a range(i, j, k): the subtable containing the rows that correspond to this range
<br>
            - a string c: the subtable containing all the rows but only the column c
<br>
            - an iterable l: the subtable that is the concatenation of all the i-th rows for all i in the iterable
<br>
        indices (Optional ``datasets.table.Table``): If not None, it is used to re-map the given key to the table rows.
<br>
            The indices table must contain one column named "indices" of type uint64.
<br>
            This is used in case of shuffling or rows selection.
<br>

<br>

<br>
    Returns:
<br>
        ``pyarrow.Table``: the result of the query on the input table
<br>
    """
<br>

        <summary>
        method | <a name='repos/datasets/src/datasets/table.py:InMemoryTable:from_pandas' href='.//repos/datasets/src/datasets/table.py#L665'>InMemoryTable:from_pandas</a>
        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>cls,<br>*args,<br>**kwargs,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>        """
<br>
        Convert pandas.DataFrame to an Arrow Table.
<br>

<br>
        The column types in the resulting Arrow Table are inferred from the
<br>
        dtypes of the pandas.Series in the DataFrame. In the case of non-object
<br>
        Series, the NumPy dtype is translated to its Arrow equivalent. In the
<br>
        case of `object`, we need to guess the datatype by looking at the
<br>
        Python objects in this Series.
<br>

<br>
        Be aware that Series of the `object` dtype don't carry enough
<br>
        information to always lead to a meaningful Arrow type. In the case that
<br>
        we cannot infer a type, e.g. because the DataFrame is of length 0 or
<br>
        the Series only contains `None/nan` objects, the type is set to
<br>
        null. This behavior can be avoided by constructing an explicit schema
<br>
        and passing it to this function.
<br>

<br>
        Args:
<br>
            df (`pandas.DataFrame`):
<br>
            schema (`pyarrow.Schema`, *optional*):
<br>
                The expected schema of the Arrow Table. This can be used to
<br>
                indicate the type of columns if we cannot infer it automatically.
<br>
                If passed, the output will have exactly this schema. Columns
<br>
                specified in the schema that are not found in the DataFrame columns
<br>
                or its index will raise an error. Additional columns or index
<br>
                levels in the DataFrame which are not specified in the schema will
<br>
                be ignored.
<br>
            preserve_index (`bool`, *optional*):
<br>
                Whether to store the index as an additional column in the resulting
<br>
                `Table`. The default of None will store the index as a column,
<br>
                except for RangeIndex which is stored as metadata only. Use
<br>
                `preserve_index=True` to force it to be stored as a column.
<br>
            nthreads (`int`, defaults to `None` (may use up to system CPU count threads))
<br>
                If greater than 1, convert columns to Arrow in parallel using
<br>
                indicated number of threads.
<br>
            columns (`List[str]`, *optional*):
<br>
               List of column to be converted. If `None`, use all columns.
<br>
            safe (`bool`, defaults to `True`):
<br>
               Check for overflows or other unsafe conversions,
<br>

<br>
        Returns:
<br>
            `datasets.table.Table`:
<br>

<br>
        Examples:
<br>
        ```python
<br>
        >>> import pandas as pd
<br>
        >>> import pyarrow as pa
<br>
        >>> df = pd.DataFrame({
<br>
            ...     'int': [1, 2],
<br>
            ...     'str': ['a', 'b']
<br>
            ... })
<br>
        >>> pa.Table.from_pandas(df)
<br>
        <pyarrow.lib.Table object at 0x7f05d1fb1b40>
<br>
        ```
<br>
        """
<br>
</li>
        </ul>

        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>self,<br>*args,<br>**kwargs,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>        """
<br>
        Convert to a pandas-compatible NumPy array or DataFrame, as appropriate.
<br>

<br>
        Args:
<br>
            memory_pool (`MemoryPool`, defaults to `None`):
<br>
                Arrow MemoryPool to use for allocations. Uses the default memory
<br>
                pool is not passed.
<br>
            strings_to_categorical (`bool`, defaults to `False`):
<br>
                Encode string (UTF8) and binary types to `pandas.Categorical`.
<br>
            categories (`list`, defaults to `empty`):
<br>
                List of fields that should be returned as `pandas.Categorical`. Only
<br>
                applies to table-like data structures.
<br>
            zero_copy_only (`bool`, defaults to `False`):
<br>
                Raise an `ArrowException` if this function call would require copying
<br>
                the underlying data.
<br>
            integer_object_nulls (`bool`, defaults to `False`):
<br>
                Cast integers with nulls to objects.
<br>
            date_as_object (`bool`, defaults to `True`):
<br>
                Cast dates to objects. If `False`, convert to `datetime64[ns]` dtype.
<br>
            timestamp_as_object (`bool`, defaults to `False`):
<br>
                Cast non-nanosecond timestamps (`np.datetime64`) to objects. This is
<br>
                useful if you have timestamps that don't fit in the normal date
<br>
                range of nanosecond timestamps (1678 CE-2262 CE).
<br>
                If `False`, all timestamps are converted to `datetime64[ns]` dtype.
<br>
            use_threads (`bool`, defaults to `True`):
<br>
                Whether to parallelize the conversion using multiple threads.
<br>
            deduplicate_objects (`bool`, defaults to `False`):
<br>
                Do not create multiple copies Python objects when created, to save
<br>
                on memory use. Conversion will be slower.
<br>
            ignore_metadata (`bool`, defaults to `False`):
<br>
                If `True`, do not use the 'pandas' metadata to reconstruct the
<br>
                DataFrame index, if present.
<br>
            safe (`bool`, defaults to `True`):
<br>
                For certain data types, a cast is needed in order to store the
<br>
                data in a pandas DataFrame or Series (e.g. timestamps are always
<br>
                stored as nanoseconds in pandas). This option controls whether it
<br>
                is a safe cast or not.
<br>
            split_blocks (`bool`, defaults to `False`):
<br>
                If `True`, generate one internal "block" for each column when
<br>
                creating a pandas.DataFrame from a `RecordBatch` or `Table`. While this
<br>
                can temporarily reduce memory note that various pandas operations
<br>
                can trigger "consolidation" which may balloon memory use.
<br>
            self_destruct (`bool`, defaults to `False`):
<br>
                EXPERIMENTAL: If `True`, attempt to deallocate the originating Arrow
<br>
                memory while converting the Arrow object to pandas. If you use the
<br>
                object after calling `to_pandas` with this option it will crash your
<br>
                program.
<br>
            types_mapper (`function`, defaults to `None`):
<br>
                A function mapping a pyarrow DataType to a pandas `ExtensionDtype`.
<br>
                This can be used to override the default pandas type for conversion
<br>
                of built-in pyarrow types or in absence of `pandas_metadata` in the
<br>
                Table schema. The function receives a pyarrow DataType and is
<br>
                expected to return a pandas `ExtensionDtype` or `None` if the
<br>
                default conversion should be used for that type. If you have
<br>
                a dictionary mapping, you can pass `dict.get` as function.
<br>

<br>
        Returns:
<br>
            `pandas.Series` or `pandas.DataFrame`: `pandas.Series` or `pandas.DataFrame` depending on type of object
<br>
        """

        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>self,<br>**kwargs,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>        """Default function generating examples for each `SplitGenerator`.
<br>

<br>
        This function preprocess the examples from the raw data to the preprocessed
<br>
        dataset files.
<br>
        This function is called once for each `SplitGenerator` defined in
<br>
        `_split_generators`. The examples yielded here will be written on
<br>
        disk.
<br>

<br>
        Args:
<br>
            **kwargs (additional keyword arguments):
<br>
                Arguments forwarded from the SplitGenerator.gen_kwargs
<br>

<br>
        Yields:
<br>
            key: `str` or `int`, a unique deterministic example identification key.
<br>
                * Unique: An error will be raised if two examples are yield with the
<br>
                    same key.
<br>
                * Deterministic: When generating the dataset twice, the same example
<br>
                    should have the same key.
<br>
                Good keys can be the image id, or line number if examples are extracted
<br>
                from a text file.
<br>
                The key will be hashed and sorted to shuffle examples deterministically,
<br>
                such as generating the dataset multiple times keep examples in the
<br>
                same order.
<br>
            example: `pyarrow.Table`, a feature table
<br>
                ready to be encoded and written to disk.
<br>
        """
<br>
</li>
        </ul>

    <details>
        <summary>
        method | <a name='repos/datasets/src/datasets/builder.py:BeamBasedBuilder:_build_pcollection' href='.//repos/datasets/src/datasets/builder.py#L2073'>BeamBasedBuilder:_build_pcollection</a>
        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>self,<br>pipeline,<br>**kwargs,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>        """Build the beam pipeline examples for each `SplitGenerator`.
<br>

<br>
        This function extracts examples from the raw data with parallel transforms
<br>
        in a Beam pipeline. It is called once for each `SplitGenerator` defined in
<br>
        `_split_generators`. The examples from the PCollection will be
<br>
        encoded and written to disk.
<br>

<br>
        <Tip warning={true}>
<br>
        Warning: When running in a distributed setup, make sure that the data
<br>
        which will be read (download_dir, manual_dir,...) and written (cache_dir)
<br>
        can be accessed by the workers jobs. The data should be located in a
<br>
        shared filesystem, like GCS.
<br>
        </Tip>
<br>

<br>
        Args:
<br>
            pipeline ([`utils.beam_utils.BeamPipeline`]):
<br>
                Apache Beam pipeline.
<br>
            **kwargs (additional keyword arguments):
<br>
                Arguments forwarded from the SplitGenerator.gen_kwargs.
<br>

<br>
        Returns:
<br>
            `beam.PCollection`: Apache Beam PCollection containing the
<br>
                example to send to `self.info.features.encode_example(...)`.
<br>

<br>
        Example:
<br>

<br>
        ```
<br>
        def _build_pcollection(pipeline, extracted_dir=None):
<br>
            return (
<br>
                    pipeline
<br>
                    | beam.Create(gfile.io.listdir(extracted_dir))
<br>
                    | beam.Map(_process_file)
<br>
            )
<br>
        ```
<br>
        """
<br>
</li>
        </ul>

        <summary>

        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>self,<br>dl_manager:  Union[DownloadManager,<br>StreamingDownloadManager],<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>        """Specify feature dictionary generators and dataset splits.
<br>

<br>
        This function returns a list of `SplitGenerator`s defining how to generate
<br>
        data and what splits to use.
<br>

<br>
        Example:
<br>

<br>
            return [
<br>
                    datasets.SplitGenerator(
<br>
                            name=datasets.Split.TRAIN,
<br>
                            gen_kwargs={'file': 'train_data.zip'},
<br>
                    ),
<br>
                    datasets.SplitGenerator(
<br>
                            name=datasets.Split.TEST,
<br>
                            gen_kwargs={'file': 'test_data.zip'},
<br>
                    ),
<br>
            ]
<br>

<br>
        The above code will first call `_generate_examples(file='train_data.zip')`
<br>
        to write the train data, then `_generate_examples(file='test_data.zip')` to
<br>
        write the test data.
<br>

<br>
        Datasets are typically split into different subsets to be used at various
<br>
        stages of training and evaluation.
<br>

<br>
        Note that for datasets without a `VALIDATION` split, you can use a
<br>
        fraction of the `TRAIN` data for evaluation as you iterate on your model
<br>
        so as not to overfit to the `TEST` data.
<br>

<br>
        For downloads and extractions, use the given `download_manager`.
<br>
        Note that the `DownloadManager` caches downloads, so it is fine to have each
<br>
        generator attempt to download the source data.
<br>

<br>
        A good practice is to download all data in this function, and then
<br>
        distribute the relevant parts to each split with the `gen_kwargs` argument
<br>

<br>
        Args:
<br>
            dl_manager (`Union[DownloadManager, StreamingDownloadManager]`):
<br>
                Download manager to download the data
<br>

<br>
        Returns:
<br>
            `list<SplitGenerator>`.
<br>
        """
<br>
</li>
        </ul>

        </summary>
        <ul>

        <ul>self,<br>**kwargs,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>        """Default function generating examples for each `SplitGenerator`.
<br>

<br>
        This function preprocess the examples from the raw data to the preprocessed
<br>
        dataset files.
<br>
        This function is called once for each `SplitGenerator` defined in
<br>
        `_split_generators`. The examples yielded here will be written on
<br>
        disk.
<br>

<br>
        Args:
<br>
            **kwargs (additional keyword arguments):
<br>
                Arguments forwarded from the SplitGenerator.gen_kwargs
<br>

<br>
        Yields:
<br>
            key: `str` or `int`, a unique deterministic example identification key.
<br>
                * Unique: An error will be raised if two examples are yield with the
<br>
                    same key.
<br>
                * Deterministic: When generating the dataset twice, the same example
<br>
                    should have the same key.
<br>
                Good keys can be the image id, or line number if examples are extracted
<br>
                from a text file.
<br>
                The key will be hashed and sorted to shuffle examples deterministically,
<br>
                such as generating the dataset multiple times keep examples in the
<br>
                same order.
<br>
            example: `dict<str feature_name, feature_value>`, a feature dictionary
<br>
                ready to be encoded and written to disk. The example will be
<br>
                encoded with `self.info.features.encode_example({...})`.
<br>
        """
<br>
</li>
        </ul>

    ```py
<br>
    >>> assert fsspec.get_filesystem_class("mock").__name__ == "DummyTestFS"
<br>
    >>> assert type(fs).__name__ == "DummyTestFS"
<br>
    >>> print(fs.glob("**"))
<br>
    ["data", "data/train.txt", "data.test.txt"]
<br>
    ```
<br>
    """

    - We use `fsspec.open` to open and read remote files. We patch the module function:
<br>
      - `open`
<br>
    - We use the "::" hop separator to join paths and navigate remote compressed/archive files. We patch the module
<br>
      functions:
<br>
      - `os.path.join`
<br>
      - `pathlib.Path.joinpath` and `pathlib.Path.__truediv__` (called when using the "/" operator)
<br>

<br>
    The patched functions are replaced with custom functions defined to work with the
<br>
    :class:`~download.streaming_download_manager.StreamingDownloadManager`.
<br>

<br>
    Args:
<br>
        module_path: Path to the module to be extended.
<br>
        download_config : mainly use use_auth_token or storage_options to support different platforms and auth types.
<br>
    """
<br>
</li>
        </ul>
    </details></ul>
</details>

        <li>Docs:<br>    """Convert Hub [script-based dataset](dataset_script) to Parquet [data-only dataset](repository_structure), so that
<br>
    the dataset viewer will be supported.
<br>

<br>
    This function:
<br>
    - makes a copy of the script on the "main" branch into a dedicated branch called "script" (if it does not already exist)
<br>
    - creates a pull request to the Hub dataset to convert it to Parquet files (and deletes the script from the main branch)
<br>

<br>
    If in the future you need to recreate the Parquet files from the "script" branch, pass the `revision="script"` argument.
<br>

<br>
    Note that you should pass the `trust_remote_code=True` argument only if you trust the remote code to be executed locally on your machine.
<br>

<br>
    Args:
<br>
        repo_id (`str`): ID of the source Hub dataset repository, in the following format: `<user>/<dataset_name>` or
<br>
            `<org>/<dataset_name>`.
<br>
        revision (`str`, *optional*): Branch of the source Hub dataset repository. Defaults to the `"main"` branch.
<br>
        token (`bool` or `str`, *optional*): Authentication token for the Hugging Face Hub.
<br>
        trust_remote_code (`bool`, defaults to `True`): Whether you trust the remote code of the Hub script-based
<br>
            dataset to be executed locally on your machine. This option should only be set to `True` for repositories
<br>
            where you have read the code and which you trust.
<br>

<br>
            <Tip warning={true}>
<br>

<br>
            `trust_remote_code` will default to False in the next major release.
<br>

<br>
            </Tip>
<br>

<br>
    Returns:
<br>
        `huggingface_hub.CommitInfo`
<br>
    """
<br>

        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>class_counts,<br>n_draws,<br>rng,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """Computes approximate mode of multivariate hypergeometric.
<br>
    This is an approximation to the mode of the multivariate
<br>
    hypergeometric given by class_counts and n_draws.
<br>
    It shouldn't be off by more than one.
<br>
    It is the mostly likely outcome of drawing n_draws many
<br>
    samples from the population given by class_counts.
<br>
    Args
<br>
    ----------
<br>
    class_counts : ndarray of int
<br>
        Population per class.
<br>
    n_draws : int
<br>
        Number of draws (samples to draw) from the overall population.
<br>
    rng : random state
<br>
        Used to break ties.
<br>
    Returns
<br>
    -------
<br>
    sampled_classes : ndarray of int
<br>
        Number of samples drawn from each class.
<br>
        np.sum(sampled_classes) == n_draws
<br>

<br>
    """
<br>
</li>
        </ul>
    </details>

<details>
<summary>
<a name='repos/datasets/src/datasets/distributed.py' href='.//repos/datasets/src/datasets/distributed.py'>repos/datasets/src/datasets/distributed.py</a>
</summary>
<ul>
    <details>
        <summary>
        function | <a name='repos/datasets/src/datasets/distributed.py:split_dataset_by_node' href='.//repos/datasets/src/datasets/distributed.py#L10'>split_dataset_by_node</a>
        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>dataset:  DatasetType,<br>rank:  int,<br>world_size:  int,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """
<br>
    Split a dataset for the node at rank `rank` in a pool of nodes of size `world_size`.
<br>

<br>
    For map-style datasets:
<br>

<br>
    Each node is assigned a chunk of data, e.g. rank 0 is given the first chunk of the dataset.
<br>
    To maximize data loading throughput, chunks are made of contiguous data on disk if possible.
<br>

<br>
    For iterable datasets:
<br>

<br>
    If the dataset has a number of shards that is a factor of `world_size` (i.e. if `dataset.n_shards % world_size == 0`),
<br>
    then the shards are evenly assigned across the nodes, which is the most optimized.
<br>
    Otherwise, each node keeps 1 example out of `world_size`, skipping the other examples.
<br>

<br>
    Args:
<br>
        dataset ([`Dataset`] or [`IterableDataset`]):
<br>
            The dataset to split by node.
<br>
        rank (`int`):
<br>
            Rank of the current node.
<br>
        world_size (`int`):
<br>
            Total number of nodes.
<br>

<br>
    Returns:
<br>
        [`Dataset`] or [`IterableDataset`]: The dataset to be used on the node at rank `rank`.
<br>
    """
<br>
</li>
        </ul>
    </details></ul>
</details>

    ```py
    >>> ds3 = _concatenate_iterable_datasets([ds1, ds2])

    ```

    """

        <summary>
        function | <a name='repos/datasets/src/datasets/iterable_dataset.py:_interleave_iterable_datasets' href='.//repos/datasets/src/datasets/iterable_dataset.py#L2290'>_interleave_iterable_datasets</a>
        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>datasets:  List[IterableDataset],<br>probabilities:  Optional[List[float]]  =  None,<br>seed:  Optional[int]  =  None,<br>info:  Optional[DatasetInfo]  =  None,<br>split:  Optional[NamedSplit]  =  None,<br>stopping_strategy:  Literal["first_exhausted",<br>"all_exhausted"]  =  "first_exhausted",<br>,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """
<br>
    Interleave several iterable datasets (sources) into a single iterable dataset.
<br>
    The new iterable dataset alternates between the sources to yield examples.
<br>
    If `probabilities = None` (default) the iterable dataset will cycles through the sources in order for each next example in the iteration.
<br>
    If `probabilities` is not `None, the iterable dataset will sample a random source according to the provided probabilities for each next examples in the iteration.
<br>

<br>
    <Added version="2.4.0"/>
<br>

<br>
    Args:
<br>
        datasets (`List[IterableDataset]`): list of datasets to interleave
<br>
        probabilities (`List[float]`, optional, default None): If specified, the new iterable dataset samples
<br>
            examples from one source at a time according to these probabilities.
<br>
        seed (`int`, optional, default None): The random seed used to choose a source for each example.
<br>
        stopping_strategy (`str`, defaults to `first_exhausted`):
<br>
            Two strategies are proposed right now.
<br>
            By default, `first_exhausted` is an undersampling strategy, i.e the dataset construction is stopped as soon as one dataset has ran out of samples.
<br>
            If the strategy is `all_exhausted`,  we use an oversampling strategy, i.e the dataset construction is stopped as soon as every samples of every dataset has been added at least once.
<br>
            Note that if the strategy is `all_exhausted`, the interleaved dataset size can get enormous:
<br>
            - with no probabilities, the resulting dataset will have max_length_datasets*nb_dataset samples.
<br>
            - with given probabilities, the resulting dataset will have more samples if some datasets have really low probability of visiting.
<br>

<br>
    Output:
<br>
        `datasets.IterableDataset`
<br>
    """
<br>

        dataset ([`IterableDataset`]):

            The iterable dataset to split by node.

        rank (`int`):

            Rank of the current node.
<br>
        world_size (`int`):
<br>
            Total number of nodes.
<br>

<br>
    Returns:
<br>
        [`IterableDataset`]: The iterable dataset to be used on the node at rank `rank`.
<br>
    """

<br>
                New features to cast the dataset to.
<br>
                The name of the fields in the features must match the current column names.
<br>
                The type of the data must also be convertible from one type to the other.
<br>
                For non-trivial conversion, e.g. `string` <-> `ClassLabel` you should use [`~Dataset.map`] to update the Dataset.

            `IterableDataset`: A copy of the dataset with casted features.
<br>

<br>
        Example:
<br>

<br>
        ```py
<br>
        >>> from datasets import load_dataset
<br>
        >>> ds = load_dataset("rotten_tomatoes", split="train", streaming=True)
<br>
        >>> ds.features
<br>
        {'label': ClassLabel(num_classes=2, names=['neg', 'pos'], id=None),
<br>
         'text': Value(dtype='string', id=None)}
<br>
        >>> new_features = ds.features.copy()
<br>
        >>> new_features["label"] = ClassLabel(names=["bad", "good"])
<br>
        >>> new_features["text"] = Value("large_string")
<br>
        >>> ds = ds.cast(new_features)
<br>
        >>> ds.features
<br>
        {'label': ClassLabel(num_classes=2, names=['bad', 'good'], id=None),
<br>
         'text': Value(dtype='large_string', id=None)}
<br>
        ```
<br>
        """

        method | <a name='repos/datasets/src/datasets/iterable_dataset.py:IterableDataset:filter' href='.//repos/datasets/src/datasets/iterable_dataset.py#L1694'>IterableDataset:filter</a>
        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>self,<br>function:  Optional[Callable]  =  None,<br>with_indices = False,<br>input_columns:  Optional[Union[str,<br>List[str]]]  =  None,<br>batched:  bool  =  False,<br>batch_size:  Optional[int]  =  1000,<br>fn_kwargs:  Optional[dict]  =  None,<br>,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>        """Apply a filter function to all the elements so that the dataset only includes examples according to the filter function.
<br>
        The filtering is done on-the-fly when iterating over the dataset.
<br>

<br>
        Args:

            function (`Callable`):

                Callable with one of the following signatures:
<br>

<br>
                - `function(example: Dict[str, Any]) -> bool` if `with_indices=False, batched=False`
<br>
                - `function(example: Dict[str, Any], indices: int) -> bool` if `with_indices=True, batched=False`
<br>
                - `function(example: Dict[str, List]) -> List[bool]` if `with_indices=False, batched=True`
<br>
                - `function(example: Dict[str, List], indices: List[int]) -> List[bool]` if `with_indices=True, batched=True`
<br>

<br>
                If no function is provided, defaults to an always True function: `lambda x: True`.
<br>
            with_indices (`bool`, defaults to `False`):
<br>
                Provide example indices to `function`. Note that in this case the signature of `function` should be `def function(example, idx): ...`.
<br>
            input_columns (`str` or `List[str]`, *optional*):
<br>
                The columns to be passed into `function` as
<br>
                positional arguments. If `None`, a dict mapping to all formatted columns is passed as one argument.
<br>
            batched (`bool`, defaults to `False`):
<br>
                Provide batch of examples to `function`.
<br>
            batch_size (`int`, *optional*, default `1000`):
<br>
                Number of examples per batch provided to `function` if `batched=True`.
<br>
            fn_kwargs (`Dict`, *optional*, default `None`):
<br>
                Keyword arguments to be passed to `function`.
<br>

<br>
        Example:
<br>

<br>
        ```py
<br>
        >>> from datasets import load_dataset
<br>
        >>> ds = load_dataset("rotten_tomatoes", split="train", streaming=True)
<br>
        >>> ds = ds.filter(lambda x: x["label"] == 0)
<br>
        >>> list(ds.take(3))
<br>
        [{'label': 0, 'movie_review': 'simplistic , silly and tedious .'},
<br>
         {'label': 0,
<br>
         'movie_review': "it's so laddish and juvenile , only teenage boys could possibly find it funny ."},
<br>
         {'label': 0,
<br>
         'movie_review': 'exploitative and largely devoid of the depth or sophistication that would make watching such a graphic treatment of the crimes bearable .'}]
<br>
        ```

        """
